Title: They Shall Not Grow Old ‚Äì New Trailer ‚Äì Now Playing In Theaters
Comment: I saw this movie at the theatre and it absolutely blew my mind.  What Peter Jackson and his team were able to do with that footage is absolutely astounding.  Especially the fact that ALL of the audio in the film (excluding the interviews) had to be recorded by the crew and then timed perfectly to match the footage.  It‚Äôs one of the most incredible cinematic achievements in the history of film, and easily one of the best documentaries I‚Äôve ever seen in my life.

Title: They Shall Not Grow Old ‚Äì New Trailer ‚Äì Now Playing In Theaters
Comment: My grandfather was an American WW1 veteran. He was a muleteer. Yes, they used a LOT of mules to move equipment and supplies. He died when I was only 6, but I remember enough about him, and have heard enough about him, to know that he came home "shell shocked", what we would call PTSD now. He absolutely never, not once, mentioned the things that happened, or what he saw. But it manifested in his "hundred yard stare", his hair-trigger temper, his reclusiveness. The war didn't affect all vets the same, but all too many of the survivors were scarred for life. They came home. There was no treatment, no therapy. They just "sucked it up" and dealt with it...or not. This documentary has made the horror he lived through truly real to me for the first time.

Title: They Shall Not Grow Old ‚Äì New Trailer ‚Äì Now Playing In Theaters
Comment:
The Great War is one of the very few wars that I have the same level of respect for for every man involved no matter which country's military he belonged to. It was one of, if not the most pointless, devastating war in modern history. The only reason so many countries became involved were due to treaties and alliances they had with their allies that were dragged into it. The only real "bad guys" were the Russians (paid the Black Hand to assassinate Austrian Archduke Franz Ferdinand) and it wasn't even their military that did it. It was a secret government plot that actually worked. Then along came the Bolshevik Revolution and fucked the country up even more which made them withdraw. Title: They Shall Not Grow Old ‚Äì New Trailer ‚Äì Now Playing In Theaters
Comment:
Dan Carlin's podcast "Blueprint for Armageddon" is almost a requirement to listen to after watching this film.  Peter Jackson viewed 100 hours of footage in which he probably saw some absolutely horrific shit.  Like the British taking 60,000 casualties (24,000 killed) on the FIRST DAY of the Somme.  Or the Battle of Passchendaele outside of Ypres... where the entire battlefield was turned into a giant "pool" of viscous mud 15 feet deep.  Soldiers would beg their buddies to shoot them even if they got stuck up to their knees because they would slowly sink and drown after 2 days.  Or falling in a shell crater full of water, and the sides are so greasy because of other decaying bodies that you will drown since you can't climb out.  Stephen King couldn't write a worse  environment.
The podcast talked about that very footage at the 1:15 mark.  Those guys are the reserve units waiting in St. John's Road trench at the Somme.  They just witnessed and heard the first wave "over the top" get completely destroyed by artillery and machine gun fire.  About 10 minutes after that very footage was filmed every person you see will be killed.... and they know it's going to happen.

We must analyze these pictures & allow them to penetrate our cognitive thinking. And I feel that Peter Jackson has done a fine job at doing that. I was both blessed & disgusted by this film. And I think that explains much of life.  We must do everything we can to avoid war. It's a cost that has no price. We must love one another as Christ loved the Church & gave Himself up for her. This film is a masterpiece & these men will not be forgotten. They fought a war that changed the face of history. But even so, we have the chance to change history by fighting spiritual battles in prayer. If all the world came into full submission to the Word of God, we would know peace. God bless ye merry gentlemen. I hate war but I am blessed to have my freedoms & that much i am thankful for. ‚ô°

Title: They Shall Not Grow Old ‚Äì New Trailer ‚Äì Now Playing In Theaters
Comment:
I'm so glad I decided to go see this in theaters when it came out! It's a beautifully and masterfully crafted documentary. The work it took to revise, edit and enhance the old footage had to have been immense. I think it's easy to forget WW1 since it happened over 100 years ago, but watching this reminded me of the sacrifice, horrid conditions and sheer terror that these young men had to endure. Most of these soldiers went from being innocent kids one day to being exposed to the most unimaginable and grotesque events in human history.

"They shall not grow old, as we that are left grow old:
Age shall not weary them, nor the years condemn.
At the going down of the sun and in the morning,
We will remember them."

- Laurence Binyon

2019: a 15-years-old girl who has a medal from Vittorio Veneto. I'm proud of this, i love my my homeland and PROUD OF ALL THE MEN WHO DEATH FOR THEIR HOMELAND!

Comment: I say this with the utmost respect but I was surprised with the amount of smiling and laughing I did in this film. I was expecting just heavy emotions throughout the majority but the men‚Äôs behavior (especially towards the camera) and humor with each other was enough to get my friend and I going. The men who tripped or stumbled because they were so focused on the camera and then laughed it off really got me. And the men who said ‚Äúhey mum!‚Äù As they walked by. There were even a few short dance moves broken out by some of them. I did feel the weight of the loss throughout the whole thing, in fact I think laughing with the men on film made it even worse. They weren‚Äôt actors or stunt men. They weren‚Äôt even from my century. But I felt more connected to them when they made me laugh. Like I knew them. And like they would‚Äôve been good boys to have a good time with. Knowing they‚Äôre all dead and that most perished within those dreadful years just seemed so much more sad. Great movie, really reminded me of the sacrifice made in WW1.

Title: They Shall Not Grow Old ‚Äì New Trailer ‚Äì Now Playing In Theaters
Comment: As an independent documentary film maker, I truly enjoyed this film because it was so authentic; not just visually, but through the audio recordings of the soldiers who told their stories. The film conveys several important lessons. Two lessons stood out to me. Lesson 1: The differences between countries that go to war is so minimal that war makes no sense. For example, the film captures a scene in which German prisoners help carry wounded British soldiers back to the medic station. They are not sure why they are at war. Lesson 2: Soldiers who return from war are not reconciled back into society by their own people. People who do not experience war cannot comprehend and identify with the experiences of the soldiers. There is a huge dis-connect between those who go to war and survive vs. those who never experience war. The beautiful authenticity of this film makes it very compelling and insightful. Therefore, I would encourage every American to see this film.

Title: They Shall Not Grow Old ‚Äì New Trailer ‚Äì Now Playing In Theaters
Comment: Just saw this film last night as my Valentines Day present. We drove over an hour away to the movie theatre to see it in West Virginia, and honestly, I would've driven much further to see it if necessary. This was one of the most amazing films I've ever seen, and one I've been wishing for since my teens. WWI is, sadly, often overlooked. It's not as easily portrayed in good vs evil terms as WWII is (something that is also not historically accurate but is much easier to film and sell). For me, it's always been frustrating to see this most important part of history all but forgotten, because these people were real and deserve to be recognised. Now, finally, someone has allowed these men to tell their own story, and in their own words. The film was done with the care and respect such a topic deserves. Thank you, Mr. Jackson, for using your prodigious talent in the service of others. I would encourage all who can to go and see this film. These men may not be superheroes but they they were heros to many people out there. Not because they went to war, but because they endured the true horror of what war really is.

Title: They Shall Not Grow Old ‚Äì New Trailer ‚Äì Now Playing In Theaters
Comment:
I saw this film last weekend.

I really can't properly articulate what an amazing achievement this documentary is. It's a deeply emotional experience, to see that old footage restored like this, and it completely succeeds at making you connect across the ages with the men who fought, suffered, persevered and survived that terrible conflict. It's not for the faint of heart (there are VERY graphic images of warfare), but it's still a film I hope will become part of regular history classes going forward.

Also, it's Peter Jackson's best contribution to cinema since the Lord of the Rings trilogy, period. He deserves all of our love and respect for the hard work he did to bring these mens' stories to life, and remind us of their heartbreaking experiences and sacrifices.

If you can see this documentary while it's still in theaters, PLEASE do so. It's an experience you will never forget, that will leave you emotionally wrung out and contemplating the value of human life afterward. 

A masterpiece.

Title: They Shall Not Grow Old ‚Äì New Trailer ‚Äì Now Playing In Theaters
Comment: I used to love going to the movies but have hardly seen anything the last few years because there's so few quality movies (IMO). I just found out about "They Shall Not Grow Old" today & plan on seeing it this weekend. My paternal great grandparents immigrated from Birmingham, England to Providence, RI in 1910. My g-grandma's younger brother, Harold, enlisted when the Great War broke out in 1914, serving in the 10th Battalion of the South Wales Borderers. I have inherited a lot of the family memorabilia, including pictures of Harold in his uniform & a letter written to him by my g-grandfather in May 1918. He never got around to mailing it & the family received word that Harold was KIA in France the following month. In 1927 my g-grandma found she was expecting again at the age of 41 (her youngest child at that time was 14). She had a boy and named him Harold after her deceased brother. A fitting tribute. Can't wait to see this documentary, it looks great!

Title: They Shall Not Grow Old ‚Äì New Trailer ‚Äì Now Playing In Theaters
Comment:
With each year that passes this moment in history sadly becomes less tangible or relevant to the younger generation it seems (and I'm by no means an old guy). My grandfather fought in the Great War at the age of 17. My son is now the same age. I cannot imagine sending him off to the horror of such an unimaginable war that was naively  thought of after as "the war to end all wars" . 
To have lived through a time where a whole generation was laid wast is beyond comprehension in today's world. There is rarely a conflict now that is not televised or streamed virtually live straight into homes. Todays wars can be watched from the distant comfort of a living room armchair on the news at 6.  I wonder how todays media would handle the British army's   57,470 casualties and 19,240 fatalities alone  at the first day of the Somme let alone how the world would react? We really have no idea today of the immense  sacrifice these young men made and the astounding carnage inflicted upon them for what  often amounted to only a few yards of a muddy field. 
The war to end all wars...How far we've come, how much we've learned. 
Hopefully this remarkable film will reconnect us to our past and remind us of how fortunate we are to have the opportunity to grow old.

Title: They Shall Not Grow Old ‚Äì New Trailer ‚Äì Now Playing In Theaters
Comment: We saw this film in a sold out movie theatre in ‚Äúmilitary city USA‚Äù ‚Äî San Antonio Texas. Title: They Shall Not Grow Old ‚Äì New Trailer ‚Äì Now Playing In Theaters
Comment:
Fantastic movie. Go see it if you can.

The heroism of these soldiers is a little complicated. The film makes abundantly clear these were kids who enlisted full of enthusiasm and did the best they could. But many of them came back broken. Indeed, one of the aftermaths of WWI was a revolt against the old world order and a sentiment that the war had been fought to preserve the monarchies and the wealthy. After WWI, monarchies across Europe fell and of course many embraced radical political systems. 

I don't think today we would just throw ourselves into war the way they did 100 years ago. People are far more questioning of their governments today, and less willing to die if they are not sure of the cause. This is probably part and parcel of the increasing democratization -- exhortations to sacrifice yourself in the name of the Queen are not likely to move too many people these days. This is all to the good, in my opinion.

And the cinematography, that looks like this was a documentary being shot and directed during that time and not just some recovered footage from the archive. I know, they can interlace the frames to make it more pleasing, but the cinematography. This is so cool! Good job Peter Jackson! You're amazing!

Title: They Shall Not Grow Old ‚Äì New Trailer ‚Äì Now Playing In Theaters
Comment:
As a teen I would go over and spend the night with my buddy, Jimbo, who lived down the street from our Chicago house. Jim's dad was dead and he lived there with his younger sister, his mom, and his deceased dad's father, Jim's "granpap".  The old man was a damn near deaf, whispy haired grouchy old son of a bitch who would have some smart ass, hard to understand, comment to me or about me every time he saw me, which would always set my dude, Jimbo, off laughing. "What...this guy a goddamn border?" or "If my kid looked like that, I'd make him stay with the neighbor's too"....Jimbo would just laugh it up. Like I said, the bathrobe wearing, shuffling old bastard was damn near deaf, so he yelled when he talked....yelled in sort of a mumble if that's possible.......and I couldn't understand jack shit that he said. I guess he didn't mean any harm, and for all I know, I was 13 or 14 years old, he was just busting my balls. But I hated the old bastard.
A day or two after Jimbo's Granpap died I was helping my friend clean out the old man's room so Jim could move in there. In a cardboard box in the closet was the old Guy's WW1 history, his uniform, his journal, letters from home, part of a gas mask, a shit ton of medals, even a pistol. I sat and read a couple of the citations that the army had given him, along with the medals. For bravery under fire, twice, the Army gave him The Citation Star (this medal would later be called The Silver Star). For twice being wounded, Purple Heart with a cluster.....This is the one that changed my feelings about the old codger. It was the second Purple Heart that sent him home
! having been awarded after an explosion went off literally next to him....blew his ear drums out. He was injured terribly, and lost most of his hearing, had a glass eye. 
Later I became a history buff, and I can't see anything, read anything, or talk about WW1 without thinking about that smart ass old bastard. And it always brings a smile to my face

Title: They Shall Not Grow Old ‚Äì New Trailer ‚Äì Now Playing In Theaters
Comment:
This movie was an EXPERIENCE. I felt like I was there. I could have watched ten more hours and remained transfixed. Amazing sights and sounds. The one thing that stood out to me the most was the personalities of the soldiers. They all seemed so positive, friendly and unspoiled. Lots of smiles and humor. Lots of making the best of a tragic situation. Lots of gratitude for basic things. It wasn't just for the camera, it was sincere good fellowship. You could feel it. Very loveable people that inspired me to be more like them. 

Sometimes the olden days seems so dreary since we only get to see grainy footage or photos with no smiles. This movie shows you that people back then were not dreary. They were full of life and optimism, they were funny and adorable. Even in the worst of situations. What heroes. This movie is a great gift to the soldiers and to us modern people. I hope it does so well that Peter Jackson makes five sequels using the rest of the footage!! üëçüëçüíñüíî

Title: They Shall Not Grow Old ‚Äì New Trailer ‚Äì Now Playing In Theaters
Comment: WOW is absolutely correct. Getting through the ninety minutes of this flick is not only a moving but also a very numbing experience. You walk out of the theater telling yourself 'What the hell? I feel like I spent the past hour entrenched in a World War I battlefield!' You honestly feel as if you are sitting right next to the soldiers on the screen and witnessing their experiences first-hand. Not at all a knock on Hollywood (as much as I'd like for it to be) but unless you've been through war yourself, no movie production can ever immerse you in the disgust and brutal realities of being in battle like this film can. It's impossible. I went in there simply expecting to see a good war documentary. But this production went way beyond and outside of my expectations. Did not at all expect to cry. But I had tears in my eyes pretty much through the second half. If you were unable to see the film in theaters then that is very unfortunate. I believe that is the best way to experience what this film has to offer. Especially if you have no military experience. This documentary does appear to be smashing box office records, so I hope additional encore screenings will be scheduled for the sake of those who were unable to see during it's first two dates. With that being said, I strongly advise those just curious about the film to proceed with caution. This is definitely NOT for the faint of heart

Comment:
A poem I wrote a few years ago using real accounts. (I tried to break up the stanzas as best I could for YouTube):

To die from a bullet seems nothing, the being remains intact, identifiable
There is an acute mental torture that comes with each ordnance, shrieking bringing a promise to each man 
I will tear you into ghastly wounds, rend you pulp a gaping.
This is a fear flesh cannot support

We heel like shepherds, paused until ordered to greet a higher entity
Over the top, the earth is troweled.
You could see a shell had burst in such a regular manner within the knot of men 
in the fresh turned earth they formed five petals, driven to the lips of the crater

Similar holes litter the front, unique to the hull they started
Brought to me a fellow draped limp upon the bunked flange, tattered Offering apologies for his cries and composure, or lack there of 
Courtesy of dying he could not help it
a fine looking boy not more than nineteen

Zealous to greet slumped neighbor, sundered belfry at mein hand
Potato masher stippled with hobnails and pommel glazed of him, it looks pretty 
His clouded eyes simple, as though lobotomized
There is no report of gunfire but in the distance, the most quiet assault
Wet Pats around me beating meat like a butcher: deafening

From darkness, wails on all sides of the riddled and faint moans
It became too Horribly obvious,
dozens of men with serious wounds have taken cover in clay battery
Too weak to move, the water had risen above them, slowly drowned in the rain Strangely lucky, to not have to worry about tomorrow

Title: They Shall Not Grow Old ‚Äì New Trailer ‚Äì Now Playing In Theaters
Comment: Went to see this film, 2D because I hate 3D, and it was amazing.  Peter Jackson deserves every possible Oscar for this amazing restoration. The care and expertise he uses in picture and sound are incomparable, from the exquisite colorization, to his use of National archive documents and his own personal collection of memorabilia to get every detail as perfect as possible.  A 30-minute "extra" documentary at the end of the credits explains in some detail how they went about collecting the film and the process of restoring the film and adding sound in places.  Narrated by actual WWI veterans which Mr. Jackson pieced together to match the scene topics.  His use of lip readers to identify dialogue, visits to the actual battle sights to get a sense of the color of foliage, is just a part of the incredible amount of work that went into this extraordinary film.  He stated that he had some 500 hours of archived film footage from WWI.  Wish only he could restore it all.  He truly took the time and care for this film that is worthy of it's subject and it is an incredible tribute to his grandfather, his great uncle that died in the last year of the war, and to any veteran, like my grandfather, or any person who knew someone in this war.  As a historian, I can not recommend this movie enough.  Rather than barely covering everything, he focuses on what his grandfather might have experienced, life for the common British soldier in WWI.  This movie should not only be seen by people interested in military history, history in general, and war documentaries, but also by people interested in film making.  If only more film makers took this much care in their craft.

Absolutely brilliant, such a necessary piece of work because so few,  so very few can even comprehend what the conditions of WWI were like, the toll it took on the entire planet.

It was worse than hell on earth, and the one quote...‚ÄùMy father let me sign at 15 years old.‚Äù A 15 year old boy strapping on 60 lbs of equipment to face almost certain death or grievous injuries.

They shall not grow old, lest we forget and thereby disrespect their incomprehensible sacrifice.

No matter the soldier or citizen, whatever country or nation they fought for, all of humanity suffered, and it is an insult to forget that. Thank you Peter Jackson for undertaking this endeavor, and thanks to all who contributed.

Title: They Shall Not Grow Old ‚Äì New Trailer ‚Äì Now Playing In Theaters
Comment:
People wonder why some of us keep going back to learn yet again about an event that's happened so long ago, especially because it has been covered so many times... they don't understand that every glimpse back gives us new insight. Not just about the historical facts, but about life itself. For me, watching something like this makes me want to live my life fuller because I don't have to experience all the terrible things the people of WW1 and others conflicts have experienced. Suddenly the mundane and routine aspects are less troublesome, and I am able to get through my day happier and more grateful for all that I have and all that has happened before me.

P.S. This is worth seeing. It really puts you in their shoes with the footage being restored. It feels very real, and suddenly WW1 feels not so distant. After all, a hundred years really isn't that long ago.

Title: They Shall Not Grow Old ‚Äì New Trailer ‚Äì Now Playing In Theaters
Comment:
Saw it last night, exceptionally good. Of course the composite frames and frame rate restoration were phenomenal, and that alone pumped so much life into the restored footage. The colorization was better than I expected. The best aspect to me was the overlaid oral history clips. From many dozens of veterans (listed at the end by unit), they provided wonderful narrative without a historian or modern narrator of any kind.

The one thing that still didn't feel fully there was the 3-D. For the restored footage in They Shall Not Grow Old, it depended on the source camera. If the depth of field was already there from a good camera, the 3-D effect worked marvelously. Where they had to force it, the result looks a little like an old ViewMaster as it always has. Still glad Jackson went that route, but am interested to see how it comes off in 2-D once it lands on a service. But all in all, worth every penny. Comes with a 30-minute making of doc after the feature.

Title: They Shall Not Grow Old ‚Äì New Trailer ‚Äì Now Playing In Theaters
Comment: I knew an old guy in his eighties, in the 1980s, who said he was an American soldier in World War One.  He said they were put in railroad boxcars, with nothing to eat but a crate of onions for 3 days, while they traveled to the front.  He also said that later they would hard boil eggs in the top of the big radiator of an Army truck by warming up the engine, bringing  the radiator water to a boil, which cooked the eggs.  Clever! (Auto engines didn't use anti-freeze in the old days, just plain water.)  His name was Bill.  He was a short, stocky, broadchested guy, who lived in  Pennsylvania, just outside Philadelphia, and he became a truck mechanic in later life.  I always remembered him telling me that.

The footage alone moves me to tears. I was never there, I will never claim to be in situations as bad as these men were, and by god they lived in a far simpler time..

But they saw more bloodshed than the world should ever see, and with every last one of them gone we have nothing but this, the stories they told and the memoirs they left behind to remember them by.

I will always salute my Brothers in Arms.

And I will always remember.

Title: They Shall Not Grow Old ‚Äì New Trailer ‚Äì Now Playing In Theaters
Comment:
I'm currently reading Barbara Tuchman's trilogy (Proud Tower/Guns of 
August/Zimmerman Telegram) simply because I've always felt like WWI gets
short shrift and I wanted to know what it was all about. This documentary couldn't have come at a better time. Thank you, Peter Jackson and team.

I especially love that PJ corrected the frame rate. I've been watching 
"Impossible Peace" (kind of as a companion to the Tuchman books) on 
Amazon video and, although I enjoy it, I hate that the people that made 
it think it's quaint to show the footage in that stupid sped-up junk. As
if black and white doesn't make for enough of a generational disconnect.

Title: They Shall Not Grow Old ‚Äì New Trailer ‚Äì Now Playing In Theaters
Comment:
I feel a need to convey to you, the reader, the incredible emotion that overtook me from watching this stunning two minute video.

The Great Was is by far one of the most brutal things to have ever occurred to humanity on any level. So brutal was this war that the United States citizenry dearly wished to avoid joining it: the Civil War still stained the fields and memories of survivors with blood.

Men would be condemned to death by incompetent leadership unable to understand the futility of "pushing the line".

Men would be burnt from within: their lungs desperately trying to find clean air as the first instances of chemical warfare were unleashed upon humanity.

And Germany would be exiled to such an incredible suffering that even Hitler and his array of strongmen and psychopaths seemed like a good option.

The feeling I felt was stronger than anything I've felt in years. I cried. I fell to my knees. I'm finally going to be able to see what this grand scar on history looked like.

I still cannot describe this emotion.

Title: They Shall Not Grow Old ‚Äì New Trailer ‚Äì Now Playing In Theaters
Comment: It's easy to distance ourselves from people in the past, but when you can actually see footage from these times, you realize that so much has changed..but one thing that remains exactly the same, is we're still just people. No different. These men in the trenches, were the same as the men in Napoleon's lines, as the men fighting in Alfred's army, as the men in the Greek phalanx, and so on..they are all just as human as us now, they feel the same, and have the same basic hopes and fears as we do. We often feel as though people in the past were different than people now, but we're not....and once you realize that through your studies, it's incredibly sobering. Especially when we have such amazing and rare footage like we do with the Great War and every war since. 1000 years from now, humans will still look back only to realize they are just the same as us now.

Comment:
I've seen a few comments about how people wanted to see the german side 

Therefore I can recommend 'All quiet on the western front'. There are 2 movies (from 1930 and 1979) and its source material is a book by Remarque. 

In german schools students have to read the book (at least when I was in school) at one point and I'm glad I did.
It's no documentary or action blockbuster, just a young german man who was disillusioned by promises of glory and found himself in one of histories greatest tragedies.

Title: They Shall Not Grow Old ‚Äì New Trailer ‚Äì Now Playing In Theaters
Comment:
Anyone who wants the last word in how cruel and grisly the Great War was need only read a poem by the war's greatest English language poet, Wilfried Owen. That poem would be "Dulce Et Decorum Eat". The title comes from the Roman poet Horace, and the full sentence is Dulce et decorum est pro patria mori."  Translation: "It is sweet and fitting to die for one's country."  And by adopting that line for his poem's title, if you expect that Owen's poem glorifies war, you are mistaken. Fair warning--the poem is not for those with a weak stomach.

And yeah, I'm excited and counting the days before Jackson's film comes out. It may only show for two days, but I'll be there for one of them. Maybe both.

Title: They Shall Not Grow Old ‚Äì New Trailer ‚Äì Now Playing In Theaters
Comment: My great-great grandpa (on my mom's side) fought for the Germans in this war. He won the Iron Cross for pulling back cannons from No Man's Land to behind German lines. Granted, I'm not saying the Germans were on the right side of the war, but to know that I had a family member that fought courageously for his country, at that time, is actually pretty awesome. He later immigrated here to the US with his wife and kids, and I believe my grandpa was the first generation from this family to be born as American. In any case, I would say WW1 is as important, if not more important, to learn from as WWII, and I can't wait to see what it was like that my great-great grandpa experienced.

Title: They Shall Not Grow Old ‚Äì New Trailer ‚Äì Now Playing In Theaters
Comment:
I wonder how many kids now days belive world war 1 was fought like how Battlefield 1 depicts it. Big open areas and cities with everyone and their mother shooting semi-auto, full autos, shotguns, and machine guns. Also superfast moving tanks and zeppelins. 


Nothing of the sort. A game that comes close to depicting the great war as it was fought is Verdun. Gritty trench by trench warfare with no man's land connecting them, and bolt action rifles were the standard with your occasional machine gunner and extremely rare submachine gunner/semi-auto user in the battlefield.

Also mortars/artillery for days.

Title: They Shall Not Grow Old ‚Äì New Trailer ‚Äì Now Playing In Theaters
Comment: 2 of my great grandfathers were German soldiers in the Great War. One was captured in 1915, returned home to Berlin afterwards and raised a family in the city during the rise of the Nazis and struggled to keep them safe as Berlin was destroyed and occupied at the end of WW2. He died in 1974. The other went home to a farm on the eastern border in what is now Poland where he died in 1935 of tuberculosis brought on by a gas attack he suffered during the conflict. I never met either of them, but I've always wondered what kind of lives they led, and the world in which they lived.

Thousands of Africans and Indians, amongst other groups, were used as soldiers by multiple countries, and thousands more used as laborers. The only difference between these troops and the troops of Europe is that once the war was done, they went back to being threatened by tyrants.

As for women, most served in non-combat roles such as nurses or began doing all the work traditionally reserved for men e.g. working in factories. They were still payed less than men. Working in the factories was dangerous, especially in munitions factories.

Stupid war that WWI.  We weren't under any threat of sorts here in the states.  The only winners were banks and the armament industries.  Young men joined up thinking they would be heroic and have an adventure and get an clean uniform to impress the ladies.  Little did they know or understand the technological developments that had been attained in warfare and weaponry.  Stupid kids.

If anyone wants to take the effort and time to find an old book, there's an excellent writing about war and profit titled "Merchants of Death" that is contemporary with WWI.  It's an good read about who actually wins wars.

Please remember that when you hear these soldiers or voice actors from English speaking countries that they had German, Eastern European, and Russian counterparts that felt the same and believed they too were just doing a job.  Dumb kids fighting each other.  None knew the horrors of war before they found themselves in it.

Title: They Shall Not Grow Old ‚Äì New Trailer ‚Äì Now Playing In Theaters
Comment:
Thank God for the British.


Not many have had the chance to be remembered in history, to live in happiness and freedom, to have great power... But none apart from the British have used this power to benefit others. The British understand what it means to be human, they believe that good of the world is good for everyone. They even let their empire, the largest in history and something very close to them, collapse and fall simply because they knew that it's hypocritical to encourage freedom and democracy while you have control over those you deem inferior. Even in the 1930s the British knew this as they were going to prevent the Italians from invading Ethiopia and Germany's expansion, but didn't because the British themselves had a massive empire and they thought it was immoral to stop them, even while Hitler and Mussolini were liars and honored nothing.

Think about this. Soldiers often fight and die for the defense of their country. But not the British. British soldiers die thousands of miles from their home in the defense of somebody else's country. In the entire history of the English (about 1000 years, 950AD) conscription has only been called on twice. For the first two years of WW1, British soldiers were all volunteers, who chose to fight and chose to do a good job. They were not forced, their country was not at a lot of risk, they went to school for 16 years and studied to get the job they wanted, a mechanic, a greengrocer, an actor. Or a soldier... They CHOSE to do this, this is why British soldiers are usually seen happy and smiling from WW1 to the present day. This is the job they chose, it's where they believed they belonged, they didn't want to be a bricklayer or an accountant, they wanted to be a soldier.

To put this into perspective. Americans have the same choice but they don't act on it. They are not taught about how lucky they are, they are not taught the truth. They are selfish and care about nobody but themselves. The generation we think about during WW1 and WW2, the strong and confident, those that just got on with things no matter how bad... They were actually characteristics of the British, the British inspired others to be like them, the world wanted to be like them. People looked up to the British like we do Americans today. But today? Look at the kids these days. Lazy, rude and no respect, they may be strong and smart but they aren't honorable, they care more about memes than tradition... These are characteristics of Americans, today people look up to Americans and want to copy them. Just think about that.

Title: They Shall Not Grow Old ‚Äì New Trailer ‚Äì Now Playing In Theaters
Comment:
The BBC showed this on Remembrance Sunday and I cannot 
recommend it highly enough.

James Morley has set up a web site where you can explore
the location of some of the British & Commonwealth casualties
from the first world war. It currently has the records of 
410,000 men & women.

   https://astreetnearyou.org/

There are a lot of entries in the US. A great deal of these seem
to be American citizens who enlisted in the Canadian armed forces.
For example:

  Private Clarence Andrew Throndson
  Canadian Infantry Works Battalion
  Date of death: 08/02/1919 (aged 30)
  Son of Andrew and Mamie Throndson,  of Farlington, Kansas, U.S.A.

  Sergeant Fredrick Bertrand Vogel 703035
  Canadian Infantry
  Date of death: 09/04/1917 (aged 30)
  Son of Phillip Francis Vogel and Margaret 
  Mary Vogel (nee Hudson), of Star Lake, Minnesota, U.S.A.

Title: They Shall Not Grow Old ‚Äì New Trailer ‚Äì Now Playing In Theaters
Comment:
My whole view of WW1 really changed when I saw this movie documentary. I knew about all the trench warfare tactics, the living conditions and how terrible the combat was, I've seen tons of dramatizations of WW1 in movies like War Horse, Passchendaele, and the Trench. But this documentary was a true eye-opener to what happened as I was listening to real first-hand experience from Veterans alongside real videos captured in the war.

The way they described going into combat and hand-to-hand fighting were so jaw-droppingly intense, it felt so different from watching a movie depicting the violence.

Title: They Shall Not Grow Old ‚Äì New Trailer ‚Äì Now Playing In Theaters
Comment:
I watched this when it was broadcast a few weeks ago in the UK by the BBC. It transforms your perception of the Great War like nothing you will have seen before. It starts off with 20 minutes of the normal black & white footage, shot at a frame rate that makes everyone seem to move faster than is natural and an old aspect ratio. You listen to the voices of long dead people as they describe their personal reasons for signing up, often years before they were legally old enough to, to their experience of training etc and then without any warning one of those bit of old footage suddenly transforms into footage so clear and colourful and smooth that you'd almost think that you were watching some modern movie. It's an utterly jaw dropping moment because it immediately makes everything you're watching more real to you.

Hats off to Peter Jackson and everyone who worked on this. You deserve the Oscar that is undoubtably going to come your way.

Title: They Shall Not Grow Old ‚Äì New Trailer ‚Äì Now Playing In Theaters
Comment:
This is all British footage of the British because the imperial war museum asked Peter Jackson to make a 30 minute documentary for the 100th anniversary.
Once Peter started, he just kept going. Sound was added to the footage using lip readers and voice actors from the area the soldiers were from.
The narration is by men who were actually there, taken from recordings made in the 1950's and 60's.
I would love to see French, German, and US versions using their own footage from that era.
Peace

Seeing them in those old b&w films all sped up just didn't tug at the heart like these clips do. Does this make sense to anyone else??

Title: They Shall Not Grow Old ‚Äì New Trailer ‚Äì Now Playing In Theaters
Comment:
I watched this on the BBC.  The moment it went from B/W to Colour stunned me.

Like many I am used to seeing silent B/W film of the Great War and I have seen previous attempts to colourise B/W, however this colour version with the added audio made it more "real".  Quite bizarre thing to say I know, but it's difficult to put into words.

It is very rare that I watch something on film or TV that makes me sit in awe of it, computer imagery and high definition are the norm so we are all used to it now, but this is something else.

Can't recommend this highly enough, if you have even a passing interested in the Great War, you must watch it.

Title: They Shall Not Grow Old ‚Äì New Trailer ‚Äì Now Playing In Theaters
Comment: Much as  you could make a complaint about how the film is a one-sided look  at a many sided story,this is still an absolutely extraordinary film. Was very lucky to nab a very late ticket to the  UK simulcast of the LFF premiere. If there's a film that this year that deserves to be seen on the big screen in 3D with an audience is this one. The theatre was dead silent as the credits rolled. The best cinema experience I have had in the past few years.  I watched  the BBC broadcast for Armistice day and while the film is still fantastic the sound design for the trench sanctions when nowhere near as immersive.
